^B@2^Z@3Today I'll be covering Jacoby Transfers over 1NT, and if there is time at the end I'll also give a @e@3 brief introduction to Texas Transfers. You can find an overview of Jacoby and Texas Transfers. They are under the section on Notrump Bidding on my website: ^*Hwww.BridgeClasses.com/notes/^*N. |pg||fp|2|at|
^-@D@D@D Jacoby Transfers over 1NT @D@D@D
^-
In all of today's hands, I'll be using a 15-17 HCP 1NT range. SOUTH will be the dealer and 1NT opening bidder in all of the hands. NORTH will be the responder.|PG||AT|

When our partner opens the bidding with 1NT, he gives us a fairly precise picture of his hand: 15-17 HCP and balanced distribution. 
^CThat means no singleton or void, and (typically) no more than one doubleton.
^CThe balanced hand patterns are: 4-3-3-3, 4-4-3-2, and 5-3-3-2|pg||at|

Knowing so much about opener's hand, it's responder's job to try and answer two key questions:
^C1) How high should we play? Part-score? game? (maybe even a slam?)
^C2) What strain should we play in... that is to say, in which suit or no trump?|pg||at|

Responder can use some simple addition to address the first question-how high.
Opposite a 15-17 HCP 1NT opener, the usual ranges for responder are:
^C0-7 points = Sign off in a part-score
^C8-9 points = Invite game
^C10-14 points = Force to game|pg||at|  

As far as which strain to play in-a suit or no trump-Jacoby Transfers really help us out. If the partnership has an 8+ card major suit fit, then that's typically where you want to play.
@D@D If responder has a 6+ card major suit, then he KNOWS the partnership has an 8+ card fit-since partner must have at least a doubleton for his 1NT opening bid. @D@D|pg||

