^B@2^Z@3Therefore, with a 6+ card major, responder can confidently insist on playing with his major suit @e@3 as trump. With only a 5 card major suit, things aren't quite so clear cut.|PG||AT| If responder has a 5 card major, the partnership is not guaranteed an 8 card fit. It is possible that opener only has a doubleton. Therefore, if responder has a 5 card major and is going to invite or force to game, he needs to get more input from partner in order to find out whether they have a 5-3 or 5-4 fit, or only a 5-2 (in which case they'd rather play in no trump instead.) |pg||at|

Now that we have a rough idea of some of the issues/questions the partnership has to deal with in these no trump auctions, the best way to get a real feel for what's going on is to go through examples... so that's what we'll do in a few minutes. There are only two bids at the core of Jacoby Transfers over 1NT:|pg||at|

^C2@D = Transfer to 2@H
^C2@H = Transfer to 2@S|pg||at|

Responder's 2@D bid does two things. 
First, it says a LITTLE bit about responder's hand that he has at least a 5 card heart suit. Can he have more than 5 hearts?|pg||at|   Yes. |pg||at|  Does it say anything about his strength?|pg||at|  No... he could have zero points, he could have 17+, or anything in between. It just says that he has at least five hearts in his hand.|pg||at|

Second, it asks opener to bid 2@H. Occasionally (if opener has a good hand with a strong fit (4+) for responder's major) opener might make a different bid (those are called Super Accepts.) But the vast majority of the time, opener is going to bid 2 of responder's shown major, like he was asked to.|pg||at|

Opener's  bid  doesn't say much of anything about his hand. He is just doing what responder asked him to. He could have 2, 3 or 4 of the asked major, and be anywhere in his 15-17 1NT range.|pg||
