^B@2^Z@3This is not a descriptive bid by opener.... he's just doing as he was told, and leaving responder @e@3 the  maximum amount of room to do whatever he was planning on doing. Once responder has made a Jacoby Transfer (which establishes that he has a 5+ card major, but doesn't say anything else about his hand) it's his second bid that goes a long way in describing the rest of his hand. Responder's options depend on his strength-whether he wants to sign off in a part score, invite game, or force to game.|pg||at|

Here is a brief overview of responder's basic options and we'll be looking at examples of each.|pg||at|

WEAK (0-7) with a 5+ card major:|pg||cp|8|at|
^C•Jacoby Transfer then PASS.|pg||cp||at|

INVITATIONAL (8-9)|pg||cp|8|at|
^C• with exactly a 5 card major: Transfer then rebid 2NT
^C• with a 6+ card major: Transfer then raise to 3 of the major |pg||cp||at|

GAME FORCING (10-14)|pg||cp|8|at|
^C• with exactly a 5 card major: Transfer then rebid 3NT (or bid a new 4+ card suit 
        if unbalanced)
^C• with a 6+ card major: insist on game in the major.|pg||cp||at|

Now, letus look at a few examples. To get the description of  bids please roll your cursor over each. Further, in the text area I will give your more information.|pg||nt||

