qx|o1|pn|sdoty,sdoty,sdoty,sdoty|st||md|1SAK86HA52DK875CQT,S9742HQT7DQJ4CAK6,S3HKJ864D632C8752,SQJT5H93DAT9CJ943,|rh||ah|Board 1|mb|1N|an|15-17 HCP, balanced|mb|p|mb|2D!|an|5+!H, any strength|mb|p|mb|2H|mb|p|mb|p|an|Weak (0-7)|mb|p|at|
^B@2^Z@3In our first example, responder has a Weak hand. With 7 or fewer points, responder knows that the partnership doesn't have the combined strength for game so his job is to stop the bidding in a part score. Responder's hand rates to be more valuable if his long suit is trump than it would be in a no trump contract so he makes a Jacoby Transfer to his major, and then passes.|pg||pc|CA|mc|9|pg||

qx|o2|pn|sdoty,sdoty,sdoty,sdoty|st||md|1S83HAQ2DKQ8CAJT65,SAJ9HJT97D43CK732,SKQ752H54D9762C94,ST64HK863DAJT5CQ8,|rh||ah|Board 2|mb|1N|an|15-17 HCP balanced|mb|p|mb|2H|an|Transfer: 5+!S, any strength|mb|p|mb|2S|mb|p|mb|p|an|Weak (0-7)|mb|p|nt|
^B@2^Z@3Responder's 2@H bid is a Jacoby Transfer to 2@S. It says that he has at least 5 spades in his hand (but says nothing about his strength), and asks opener to bid 2@S
^-** Note that opener bids 2@S as he was told to, even though he only has a doubleton **
^-This is EXTREMELY important.  As opener, you do NOT get to ignore partner's transfer just because you don't like his suit. Responder is the one in charge at this point-he knows a lot about opener's hand, and opener knows very little about his.|pg||nt|
^B@2^Z@3 As this example shows, when responder has a Weak hand (0-7) with only a 5 card major, he isn't guaranteed an 8 card trump fit.  When he transfers he is hoping that opener has at least 3 card support (which he will the majority of the time), but once in a while you will find yourself in a 5-2 fit. That's just the way it is... responder has to take the action that will work out best the majority of the time. |pg||nt|
^B@2^Z@3 It's important for responder to transfer to his major suit when he has a hand like this one, because his hand will usually be more valuable in a trump contract than in no trump. If spades are trump, responder's hand is going to contribute at least 2-3 spade tricks.  But imagine if NS played in 1NT instead... North's hand would only be worth ONE trick.|pg||nt|
^B@2^Z@3 South, with only two spades in his hand, would never be able to both establish and then cash out North's spade suit. He would get completely cut off from the dummy and responder's spades would hardly contribute anything at all. At least with spades as trump-even if the partnership only has a 5-2 fit-north's long spades are going to be worth some tricks. And if opener does have 3+ spades (which he will most of the time) we would certainly want to play in a spade contract.|pg||nt|
^B@2^Z@3 So in the long run, you're better off playing these hands in 2 of responder's major. Will there be hands that would have been better played in 1NT? Yes... but only a small percentage of them. With a Weak (0-7) hand responder has to make a choice-pass or transfer to his 5+ card major suit-and transferring will work out best the large majority of the time.|pg||pc|HJ|mc|9|pg||nt||

qx|o3|pn|sdoty,sdoty,sdoty,sdoty|st||md|1SAQHJ965DK862CKQ8,S983HAT83DQJT4CT6,SJ76542H42DA9C972,SKTHKQ7D753CAJ543,|rh||ah|Board 3|mb|1N|an|15-17 HCP balanced|mb|p|mb|2H|an|Transfer: 5+!S, any strength|mb|p|mb|2S|mb|p|mb|p|an|Weak (0-7)|mb|p|nt|
^B@2^Z@3Again, responder has a Weak (0-7) hand that doesn't have any game interest, so he makes a Jacoby Transfer to his 5+ card major (this time he's lucky enough to have a 6 card spade suit) and then  passes. And not to beat a dead horse, but again note that opener COMPLETES THE TRANSFER by bidding 2@S, even though he only has a doubleton spade in his hand. Opener does not get to bid anything other than 2@S simply because he doesn't particularly like partner's spade suit. RESPONDER is the one in charge at this point, not opener.|pg||nt|	
^B@2^Z@3So far, we've seen that with a Weak hand (0-7) and a 5+ card major suit, responder transfers to his major and then passes. His goal there is simply to put the partnership in the best part score, and 2 of responder's major will usually play better than 1NT. That isn't guaranteed, but all we can do is go with the action that will turn out best the most often. With an Invitational strength hand (8-9 points), responder is strong enough to take two bids.|pg||pc|DQ|mc|9|pg||nt||

qx|o4|pn|sdoty,sdoty,sdoty,sdoty|st||md|1SAJHKT7DQ875CAKT9,SQ9764H65DT2CQJ42,ST52HAJ843DKJ6C73,SK83HQ92DA943C865,|rh||ah|Board 4|mb|1N|an|15-17 HCP, balanced|mb|p|mb|2D|an|Xfer to 2!H: 5+!H, any strength|mb|p|mb|2H|mb|p|mb|2N|an|inv (8-9) with exactly 5!H|mb|p|mb|4H|an|max with 3+!H|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|nt|^B@2^Z@3With an Invitational strength hand (8-9 points), responder is strong enough to take two bids. Responder starts by bidding 2@D ... a Jacoby Transfer to 2@H, telling partner that he has at least five hearts and asking him to bid 2@H. Responder's SECOND BID here is critical. With invitational strength (8-9), responder has to do one of two things after his transfer:|PG||cp|8|at|
^c* rebid 2NT with exactly a 5 card suit
^C* raise to 3 of his major with a 6+ card suit.|pg||CP||nt|
^B@2^Z@3 Responder's 2NT rebid here says: "Partner, I have invitational strength and EXACTLY a 5 card heart suit. I need your help, because I'm not sure whether we should play in hearts or  no trump, or stop in a part score or bid game."
^B@2^Z@3 Now the ball is in opener's court. There are two issues he needs to address;|pg||nt|
^B@2^Z@31. Should the partnership play in hearts or in no trump? If opener has 3+ hearts, the partnership has a 5-3 fit and should play in hearts. If opener only has a doubleton, then the partnership does not have a heart fit and should play in no trump instead.|pg||at|
^B@2^Z@32. Does opener want to accept the game invite (is he in the upper end of his no trump range), or stop in a part score (if he's on the lower end.)|pg||nt|
^B@2^Z@3 In this case, opener has 3 hearts .... so he knows they have a 5-3 heart fit, and therefore should play in a heart contract. Opener is also on the upper end of his range, so he should bid a game.|pg||pc|CQ|mc|11|pg||nt||

qx|o5|pn|sdoty,sdoty,sdoty,sdoty|st||md|1SATHAK43DT75CAQ86,SJ8HQJT6DK432CJ32,SQ6532H92DA96CKT4,SK974H875DQJ8C975,|rh||ah|Board 5|mb|1N|mb|p|mb|2H|an|xfer to 2!S: 5+!S, any strength|mb|p|mb|2S|mb|p|mb|2N|an|inv (8-9) with exactly 5!S|mb|p|mb|3N|an|max with only 2 spades|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|at|^B@2^Z@3 Responder's 2@H bid was a Jacoby Transfer to 2@S. It showed at least a 5 card spade suit, but didn't say anything else about his hand. Responder's 2NT rebid clarifies both his spade LENGTH and his overall STRENGTH. He shows an invitational strength hand (8-9 points) with -exactly- a 5 card spade suit. |pg||nt|
^B@2^Z@3 Opener is at the top of his range, so he is going to accept the game invite. With his doubleton spade, he knows that they only have a 5-2 spade fit, and should therefore play in no trump instead of in spades. Put the two together, and with 15 counts opener usually declines an invite, and with 17 he should always accept. With 16, it can go either way ... it really depends on the hand, and how well you think it'll fit with your partners. There is no "rule" for 16 counts.|pg||pc|HQ|mc|9|pg||nt||

qx|o6|pn|sdoty,sdoty,sdoty,sdoty|st||md|1SKQ52HJ4DKQ32CA92,SA987HQT9D75CKQ53,SJ3HK8652DA6CJ764,ST64HA73DJT984CT8,|rh||ah|Board 6|mb|1N|mb|p|mb|2D|an|xfer to 2!H: 5+!H, any strength|mb|p|mb|2H|mb|p|mb|2N|an|inv (8-9) with exactly 5!H|mb|p|mb|p|an|minimum with only 2!H|mb|p|at|
^B@2^Z@3Again, responder's transfer followed by 2NT shows an invitational strength hand (8-9 pts) with exactly a 5 card heart suit. Opener has to think about two things: 
^CIs there a heart fit? Does he want to accept the invite?
In this case, the answer to both questions is "no."  They do not have a heart fit, and opener is minimum and wants to stop in a part score.  So he passes out 2NT as the final contract. |pg||pc|S7|mc|7|pg||nt||

qx|o7|pn|sdoty,sdoty,sdoty,sdoty|st||md|1SAJ3H64DKQ43CAJ63,S76HAK532DJ65C942,SKT942HQ87D82CKT8,SQ85HJT9DAT97CQ75,|rh||ah|Board 7|mb|1N|mb|p|mb|2H|an|xfer to 2!S: 5+!S, any strength|mb|p|mb|2S|mb|p|mb|2N|an|inv (8-9) with exactly 5!S|mb|p|mb|3S|an|min with 3+!S|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|nt|^B@2^Z@3 We don't see hands like this too often for some reason, but if opener has a fit but doesn't want to play in game, he can sign-off in 3 of responder's major.|at|
^B@2^Z@3 This responding hand makes people unhappy, but it's an important one to understand. When responder has invitational strength, his options for second bid are limited. When he rebids 2NT, he shows invitational points with exactly a 5 card spade suit... which is what he has. He does NOT, however, guarantee a balanced hand.|pg||nt|^B@2^Z@3 If opener has a fit but doesn't want to play in game, he can sign-off in 3 of responder's major. Responder should not rebid his major unless he has at least 6 of them. And he can't bid a new suit either, because that is a game forcing bid. So he has to rebid 2NT, and trust that opener is going to do what he's supposed to do. IF THE PARTNERSHIP HAS A 5-3 SPADE FIT, opener is going to put it back in spades.|pg||pc|HA|mc|9|pg||nt||


