qx|o8|pn|sdoty,sdoty,sdoty,sdoty|st||md|1SK4HA982DKT73CAQT,S92HK76DAJ82C8753,SAJ875HQJ3D5CJ642,SQT63HT54DQ964CK9,|rh||ah|Board 8|mb|1N|mb|p|mb|2H|an|xfer to 2!S: 5+!S, any strength|mb|p|mb|2S|mb|p|mb|2N|an|inv (8-9) with exactly 5!S|mb|p|mb|3N|an|max with only 2!S|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|NT|^B@2^Z@3In this hand, obviously responder isn't thrilled at the idea of playing in no trump with an unbalanced hand, but the only time opener is going to leave it in no trump is if he only has a doubleton spade and if the partnership only has a 5-2 spade fit, you don't really want to play in a spade contract with this responding hand.|pg||nt|
^B@2^Z@3Plus, if opener is short in spades, he rates to have some length/strength in partner's short suit... so you don't have to be overly concerned about being wide open in diamonds. With a hand like this one, responder would like to play in spades... IF they have a spade fit. And you accomplish that just fine by re-bidding 2NT. Since it is opener's job to put you back in spades if he has 3+ card support for you. If responder has game values (10-14), we see the same concept at work.|PG||
