qx|o13|pn|sdoty,sdoty,sdoty,sdoty|st||md|1SAKT3H432DA97CA83,SQ976HJ5D843CJ942,S2HAKT87DJ652CKT7,SJ854HQ96DKQTCQ65,|rh||ah|Board 13|mb|1N|mb|p|mb|2D|an|xfer to 2!H: 5+!H, any strength|mb|p|mb|2H|mb|p|mb|3D|an|natural, game forcing|mb|p|mb|3H|an|3+ hearts|mb|p|mb|4H|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|nt|^B@2^Z@3 When responder has the strength for game (10-14) and exactly a 5 card major, he has an option available that he didn't when he only had invitational points. If his hand is unbalanced, rather than simply rebidding 3NT, he has the option of showing a second suit.|pg||nt|
^B@2^Z@3 Responder's 3@D bid says that he has
    * exactly 5 hearts
    * 4+ diamonds
    * game values (10+ ... this bid is game forcing) and usually his hand will be unbalanced
^-** The partnership must reach game **
^-
|pg||nt|^B@2^Z@3 Not surprisingly, opener's first priority is to show a fit for responder's heart suit if he has one. From there responder can simply raise to game, or he might start cue-bidding for slam if his hand is that strong (typically 15+.)|
